d rather than loose. Maybe I should explore using `git unpack-objects` or another approach to convert the pack into loose objects that go-git can find.\\n\\nActually, the simplest solution is probably to just use `git cat-file` to read the blob after the fetch completes — that avoids all the complexity of trying to refresh the storer or unpack the repository.\\n\\nNow I'm implementing the `File` method with a fast path that tries a direct read first, then falls back to fetching the blob by hash if it's not available locally.\\n\\nWriting the fetch logic... I'm considering a few different approaches here: adding a `BlobReadFunc` to `FetchingTree` so the caller can provide a custom blob reader, or enhancing `BlobResolver` with a git CLI fallback. But the simplest solution might be to skip `FetchBlobsByHash` entirely and have `FetchingTree.File()` read blobs directly via `git cat-file` when they're not in the local storer — though I'm realizing `cat-file` only works with local objects anyway.\\n\\nAfter `fetch-pack` completes though, those objects should be local in the new pack file, so `git cat-file` would work. I'll add a helper function to read blob content through the git CLI and construct an in-memory File from it. But I need to be careful about dependencies — the checkpoint package currently doesn't import `os/exec`, and adding that might not be the cleanest approach. Maybe instead I should refactor `BlobFetchFunc` into a `BlobReadFunc` that handles both fetching and returning the blob content.\\n\\nActually, thinking about this from the caller side — the simplest fix might be to skip `FetchingTree` entirely in `resume.go` and handle blob fetching directly using `git cat-file`. That would require significant refactoring though. The cleanest path forward is probably to add a `BlobContentFunc` callback to `FetchingTree` that reads blob content by hash, then use that in the `File()` method when the normal fetch doesn't make the blob visible to the storer. Let me im